  <h2>About Bajaj Auto</h2>
  
  <p>Bajaj Auto Limited, an Indian multinational automotive company based in Pune, is a key player in the global automotive sector. With a diverse product portfolio encompassing motorcycles, scooters, and auto rickshaws, Bajaj Auto has emerged as a powerhouse within the Bajaj Group. Founded by Jamnalal Bajaj in the 1940s in Rajasthan, the company has evolved into the world's third-largest motorcycle manufacturer and the largest producer of three-wheelers globally.</p>
  
  <h3>Market Leadership and Achievements</h3>
  
  <p>Bajaj Auto achieved remarkable milestones, becoming the world's most valuable two-wheeler company in December 2020, crossing a market capitalization of ₹1 trillion (US$13 billion). It holds the distinction of being the world's largest three-wheeler manufacturer and stands as the second-largest motorcycle manufacturer in India.</p>
  
  <h2>History</h2>
  
  <h3>1945–1986: Evolution and Expansion</h3>
  
  <p>Established on November 29, 1945, as M/s Bachraj Trading Corporation Private Limited, Bajaj Auto initially focused on importing and selling two- and three-wheelers in India. In 1959, it obtained a license to manufacture two-wheelers and three-wheelers, and in 1960, it transitioned into a public limited company. The introduction of motorcycles in 1986 marked a significant shift, transforming the company into a prominent two-wheeler manufacturer.</p>
  
  <h3>Strategic Alliances and Corporate Restructuring</h3>
  
  <p>In 1984, Bajaj Auto entered a technical assistance agreement with Kawasaki, leading to expanded production and sales of motorcycles. The early 2000s witnessed the acquisition of a controlling stake in Tempo Firodia, later renamed "Bajaj Tempo." However, in 2005, the company underwent a name change to Force Motors. Notably, Bajaj Auto's strategic investment journey extended to Austrian rival KTM, acquiring a 48% non-controlling share by 2020.</p>
  
  <h3>Recent Ventures and Collaborations</h3>
  
  <p>In 2017, Bajaj Auto collaborated with Triumph Motorcycles Ltd to develop mid-capacity motorcycles. The same year, the sales and services partnership with Kawasaki in India concluded, with Bajaj and Kawasaki maintaining their relationship in overseas markets. Bajaj Auto further diversified its investments in 2019 by injecting ₹57 crore ($8 million) into bicycle and electric scooter rental startup Yulu.</p>
  
